<TITLE> Dhaka stocks fall, led by Dutch Bangla </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, March 24 (bdnews24.com)Dhaka stocks slumped on Monday, influenced by the price adjustment of Dutch Bangla Bank and profit-taking by investors. Corrected An official of brokerage house Latif Securities told bdnews24.com that investors had sold off scrips which gained Sunday, including under-performing Z category issues. DSE chief executive Salahuddin Ahmed said the selling spree and price adjustment of Dutch Bangla Bank had led the indices to fall Monday. "As some prices went up for the last couple of trading days investors are locking in profits and the price adjustment of Dutch Bangla Bank heavily influenced the indices to go down," he said. After adjustments, Dutch Bangla Bank's market capitalisation fell from Tk 2,000 crore to Tk 500 crore. Shares of the bank lost 73.05 percent from Sunday's close, ending on Tk 3494. The general index remained steady from the last two and a half hours to finish lower. The benchmark DGEN or general index closed down 84.41 points, or 2.81 percent, to end on 2913.34. The DSI or all-share price index finished at 2467.70, down 63.56 points, or 2.51 percent. The bourse's blue-chip DSE-20 however advanced 0.84 points, or 0.03 percent, to end on 2264.41. Turnover on the country's prime bourse slumped to 2.30 billion from Sunday's Tk 3.16 billion, from 17,271,995 traded shares. Losers beat gainers 144 to 93, with 11 issues remaining unchanged. The day saw the prices of pharmaceuticals and power companies' fall due to profit-taking, while mutual funds closed mixed and banks were back on track with rising prices. Square Pharma topped the turnover board, falling 2.31 percent to close at Tk 3808. Beximco Pharma followed; ending on Tk 78.10, down 2.13 percent. AB Bank gained after a couple of day's losses, ending 4.49 percent up to close at Tk 3266.75. DESCO lost 1.63 percent to end on 1040.25, while Power Grid Company of Bangladesh finished at Tk 652.75, down 1.76 percent. Among other scrips on the turnover board: ICB 1st NRB Mutual Fund, Lafarge Surma Cement and Uttara Bank advanced. ACI and Dutch Bangla Bank declined. All indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange finished up. The CSCX or selective categories index gained 23.44 points, or 0.46 percent, to end on 5038.66. The CASPI or all-share price index finished at 7851.37, up 33.48 points, or 0.42 percent. The CSE-30 blue-chip advanced 50.02 points, or 0.74 percent, to close at 6804.16. Turnover on the port city's bourse also fell to Tk 346.75 million from Tk 563.79 million the previous day. Of the issues traded, 52 advanced, 84 lost and three held steady. bdn
